INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '513dbd9a-3cbe-4a11-882d-3983cc1017ec',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Redis Streams — Horizontal Consumer Scaling with Consumer Groups$escape$,
  $escape$Redis Streams' consumer group model is the right primitive for horizontally scaling message processing. Unlike Pub/Sub (which fans out every message to every subscriber), a consumer group distributes messages across consumers — each message is delivered to exactly one consumer in the group.

Use `XREADGROUP` with a unique consumer name per instance. Redis tracks pending entries per consumer in the PEL (Pending Entries List). If a consumer dies mid-processing, another can claim its stalled messages via `XAUTOCLAIM` after a visibility timeout.

There are no partitions in Redis Streams the way Kafka has them — a single stream is the unit of distribution. To scale beyond what one stream can handle, manually shard: route by `user_id % N` into streams like `events:0`, `events:1`, ..., `events:N-1`, and assign dedicated consumer groups per shard. Adding shards requires rebalancing your routing logic and spinning up new consumer group instances — Redis itself does not rebalance automatically. Keep shard count stable; resharding means rehashing keys and migrating in-flight PEL entries manually.$escape$,
  $escape$# Create group on stream ($ = only new messages)
XGROUP CREATE events:0 workers $ MKSTREAM

# Consumer reads up to 10 messages, blocks 2s if empty
XREADGROUP GROUP workers consumer-1 COUNT 10 BLOCK 2000 STREAMS events:0 >

# Acknowledge processed message
XACK events:0 workers 1712000000000-0

# Claim messages pending > 30s from dead consumers
XAUTOCLAIM events:0 workers consumer-2 30000 0-0 COUNT 50$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
